@article{Alsing2016,
annote = {Read 31/5–2/7/19.

Really nice way of doing shear power spectrum inference that naturally accounts for noise and an arbitrary mask. Not too slow either: their example, inferring auto- and cross-spectra for E- and B-modes and 2 redshift bins on 128x128 pixel maps took {\~{}}500 hours of computing time.

Seveal relevant references highlighted.

The process iteratively alternates between generating the shear field and the underlying power spectrum, and is able to handle anisotropic noise. It turns out that anisotropic noise is difficult to handle computationally, so they overcome this by using a 'messenger field' which separates out the isotropic and anisotropic parts of the noise and simplifies things computationally. Specifically, it means that any matrices that require inversion in order to sample from the relevant probability distributions are sparse, which isn't the case without a messenger field. When they aren't sparse, you can't really invert them in practice because they're so big.

