annote = {Read 4-5/1/21.

See also lab book 5/1/20 for notes.

They present the covariance used for the DES Y3 3x2pt correlation function analysis, which is essentially CosmoLike with an fsky reweighting approach to the cut sky.

Most of the paper is testing the approximations that go into this.

They also test the accuracy of the Gaussian likelihood, though in a pretty brief test. For this, they use (I think exact) expressions for the full-sky 2PCF skewness, apply an fsky factor to get (approximate) cut-sky 2PCF skewness, then sample from a lognormal distribution having this skewness. They also repeat for 5x this skewness. In both cases they find no difference in the distribution of best-fit $\sigma$8 compared to the distribution predicted from a Gaussian likelihood.

They test many aspects of the covariance. Most aren't worth detailing here, but some interesting ones:

- The effect of finite $\theta$ bin width, i.e. the fact that real 2PCF estimates are for a $\theta$ bin not a point $\theta$. Interesting because neglecting this has a large effect. They present some expressions about how to handle this exactly.

- Non-Gaussian covariance. They find that in their case, if they replace it with a lognormal approximation or neglect it entirely it has negligible impact on paramater constraints. This is an interesting (and convenient!) result, but they stress it might not extend to other analysis setups.

- Cut sky, in particular the fsky reweighting approximation. To test this, they develop a "beyond fsky" approach:
--- They show that you can write the covariance of cut-sky 2PCFs as a linear combination of pseudo-Cl covariances.
